<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<display version="2.0.0">
  <name>Actions</name>
  <height>635</height>
  <widget type="label" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Label</name>
    <class>TITLE</class>
    <text>Actions</text>
    <x use_class="true">0</x>
    <y use_class="true">0</y>
    <width>281</width>
    <height>31</height>
    <font use_class="true">
      <font name="Header 1" family="Liberation Sans" style="BOLD" size="22.0">
      </font>
    </font>
    <foreground_color use_class="true">
      <color name="Text" red="0" green="0" blue="0">
      </color>
    </foreground_color>
    <transparent use_class="true">true</transparent>
  </widget>
  <widget type="label" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Label_1</name>
    <class>SECTION</class>
    <text>Purpose</text>
    <y>41</y>
    <width>331</width>
    <height>30</height>
    <font use_class="true">
      <font name="Default Bold" family="Liberation Sans" style="BOLD" size="14.0">
      </font>
    </font>
    <foreground_color use_class="true">
      <color name="Text" red="0" green="0" blue="0">
      </color>
    </foreground_color>
    <transparent use_class="true">true</transparent>
  </widget>
  <widget type="label" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Label_4</name>
    <text>Actions are typically defined on the 'Action Button' widget.

Actions can
- Open another display file,
  either as a new panel or by replacing the current panel.
- Write a value to a PV
- Start scripts
- Execute external commands
</text>
    <y>71</y>
    <width>561</width>
    <height>180</height>
  </widget>
  <widget type="label" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Label_5</name>
    <text>Actions can be assigned to any widget.
To invoke them, the user then needs to invoke the context menu
on the widget (right-click) and select the desired action.
The use of 'Action Buttons' should be preferred because
it is more obvious to end users.</text>
    <y>360</y>
    <width>561</width>
    <height>110</height>
    <font>
      <font name="Comment" family="Liberation Sans" style="ITALIC" size="14.0">
      </font>
    </font>
  </widget>
  <widget type="action_button" version="3.0.0">
    <name>Action Button</name>
    <actions>
      <action type="open_display">
        <file>01_main.bob</file>
        <target>replace</target>
        <description>back to main</description>
      </action>
    </actions>
    <x>440</x>
    <y>140</y>
    <width>140</width>
    <tooltip>$(actions)</tooltip>
  </widget>
  <widget type="action_button" version="3.0.0">
    <name>Action Button_1</name>
    <actions>
      <action type="write_pv">
        <pv_name>$(pv_name)</pv_name>
        <value>Hello</value>
        <description>Write Hello</description>
      </action>
      <action type="write_pv">
        <pv_name>$(pv_name)</pv_name>
        <value>Bye</value>
        <description>Write Bye</description>
      </action>
    </actions>
    <pv_name>loc://text("some_PV")</pv_name>
    <x>440</x>
    <y>251</y>
    <width>140</width>
  </widget>
  <widget type="textupdate" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Text Update</name>
    <pv_name>loc://text("some_PV")</pv_name>
    <x>320</x>
    <y>251</y>
    <width>110</width>
    <height>30</height>
  </widget>
  <widget type="label" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Label_6</name>
    <text>Typical actions buttons have exactly one
action assigned to them.
Clicking the button invokes that action.

If an action button has multiple actions
assigned, a drop-down allows invoking
one of them at a time.</text>
    <y>230</y>
    <width>300</width>
    <height>130</height>
  </widget>
  <widget type="action_button" version="3.0.0">
    <name>Action Button_2</name>
    <actions>
      <action type="command">
        <command>echo "Hello, World"</command>
        <description>Print 'Hello'</description>
      </action>
    </actions>
    <x>440</x>
    <y>480</y>
    <width>140</width>
    <tooltip>$(actions)</tooltip>
  </widget>
  <widget type="action_button" version="3.0.0">
    <name>Action Button_3</name>
    <actions>
      <action type="command">
        <command>/opt/X11/bin/xterm</command>
        <description>Start XTerm (Mac)</description>
      </action>
    </actions>
    <x>440</x>
    <y>560</y>
    <width>140</width>
    <tooltip>$(actions)</tooltip>
  </widget>
  <widget type="action_button" version="3.0.0">
    <name>Action Button_4</name>
    <actions>
      <action type="command">
        <command>pwd</command>
        <description>Print CWD</description>
      </action>
    </actions>
    <x>440</x>
    <y>520</y>
    <width>140</width>
    <tooltip>$(actions)</tooltip>
  </widget>
  <widget type="label" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Label_2</name>
    <class>SECTION</class>
    <text>External Commands</text>
    <y>460</y>
    <width>331</width>
    <height>30</height>
    <font use_class="true">
      <font name="Default Bold" family="Liberation Sans" style="BOLD" size="14.0">
      </font>
    </font>
    <foreground_color use_class="true">
      <color name="Text" red="0" green="0" blue="0">
      </color>
    </foreground_color>
    <transparent use_class="true">true</transparent>
  </widget>
  <widget type="label" version="2.0.0">
    <name>Label_3</name>
    <text>Actions that invoke external commands are executed
by the operating system in the directory of the display file,
unless an absolute path is provided.

The standard output and the error output of the command
are printed as log messages.
</text>
    <y>480</y>
    <width>410</width>
    <height>110</height>
  </widget>
  <widget type="action_button" version="3.0.0">
    <name>Action Button_5</name>
    <actions>
      <action type="command">
        <command>/usr/bin/xterm</command>
        <description>Start XTerm (Linux)</description>
      </action>
    </actions>
    <x>440</x>
    <y>600</y>
    <width>140</width>
    <tooltip>$(actions)</tooltip>
  </widget>
</display>
